--- body ---
## Context

`test_golden_values.py::TestGoldenValues::test_method_matches_golden` fails for all 10 methods with:

```
AssertionError: S1_MMD: shape mismatch — golden (108, 5), fresh (96, 5)
```

The golden CSVs in `tests/fixtures/golden/` were generated when the smoke fixture corpus had 108 works.
The current smoke fixture has 96 works. The shape mismatch causes all golden-value tests to fail.

This is data drift, not a code regression. The golden values need to be regenerated on any machine
where `CLIMATE_FINANCE_DATA` points to the current smoke fixture.

## Relevant files

- `tests/fixtures/golden/tab_div_*.csv` — stale golden CSV files (108 rows)
- `tests/test_golden_values.py` — compares fresh output to golden; marks `@pytest.mark.slow`
- `scripts/compute_divergence.py` — the script that generates divergence CSVs

## Actions

1. Identify where the golden files are generated (grep for `update-golden` or similar in Makefile/scripts).
2. Run the regeneration command on padme with the current smoke fixture:
   ```bash
   make regression-update   # or equivalent
   ```
   Or manually:
   ```bash
   for method in S1_MMD S2_energy S3_sliced_wasserstein S4_frechet \
                 L1 G1_pagerank G2_spectral G5_pref_attachment G6_entropy G8_betweenness; do
     CLIMATE_FINANCE_DATA=tests/fixtures/smoke \
     uv run python scripts/compute_divergence.py \
       --method $method --output tests/fixtures/golden/tab_div_${method}.csv
   done
   ```
3. Commit the updated golden CSVs.

## Test

```bash
pytest tests/test_golden_values.py -v  # should pass for all 10 methods
```

## Exit criteria

- [ ] `pytest tests/test_golden_values.py` passes (all 10 methods, shape and value match)
- [ ] Golden CSVs committed with message "chore: regenerate golden values (96-work smoke fixture)"

## Notes

- C2ST golden values may also need regeneration — check `test_golden_values.py` for full method list.
- `test_null_model_c2st.py::TestC2STNullModelSmoke` timeouts (>30s) can be addressed in the same
  session: increase `--timeout` on those integration tests (currently 30s; 120s would be sufficient).
